{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2016}} {{Use Australian English|date=April 2016}} {{for|other countries which use this rank|Vice admiral}} {{Infobox military rank | name = Vice admiral | image = Royal Australian Navy OF-8.svg | image_size = 70px | caption = The VADM insignia | image2 = Royal Australian Navy (sleeves) OF-8.svg | image_size2 = 70px | caption2 = | country = {{flag|Australia}} | service branch = {{navy|Australia}} | abbreviation = VADM | rank = Vice Admiral | NATO rank = [[Ranks and insignia of NATO armies officers#Officers (OF 1â€“10)|OF-8]] | Non-NATO rank = [[five-star rank|O-9]] | formation = {{start date|1936|07|12|df=y}} | abolished = | higher rank = [[Admiral (Australia)|Admiral]] | lower rank = [[Rear admiral (Australia)|Rear admiral]] | equivalents = {{bulleted list|{{nowrap|[[Lieutenant general (Australia)|Lieutenant general]] ([[Australian Army|Army]])}}|{{nowrap|[[Air marshal (Australia)|Air marshal]] ([[Royal Australian Air Force|RAAF]]) }} }} | history = }} '''Vice admiral''' (abbreviated as '''VADM''') is the second-highest active rank of the [[Royal Australian Navy]] and was created as a direct equivalent of the [[United Kingdom|British]] rank of [[Vice_admiral#United_Kingdom|vice admiral]]. It is a [[three-star rank]]. The rank is held by the [[Chief of Navy (Australia)|Chief of Navy]] and, when the positions are held by navy officers, by the [[Vice Chief of the Defence Force (Australia)|Vice Chief of the Defence Force]], the [[Chief of Joint Operations (Australia)|Chief of Joint Operations]], or the [[Chief Capability Development Group]].
Vice admiral is a higher rank than [[Rear admiral (Australia)|rear admiral]], but lower than [[Admiral (Australia)|admiral]]. Vice admiral is the equivalent of [[Air marshal (Australia)|air marshal]] in the [[Royal Australian Air Force]] and [[Lieutenant general (Australia)|lieutenant general]] in the [[Australian Army]].
Since the mid-1990s, the insignia of a Royal Australian Navy vice admiral is the [[Crown of St. Edward]] above a crossed sabre{{efn|Usually in Commonwealth countries a [[scimitar]] is used in the insignia, which is an open-handled weapon; the sabre has a closed handle.}} and baton, above three silver stars, above the word "AUSTRALIA".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.navy.gov.au/about/organisation/uniform-ranks |title=Uniform Ranks |work=Royal Australian Navy |publisher=[[Australian Government]] |date= |accessdate=17 April 2016 }}</ref> The stars have eight points{{efn|The stars have eight points, unlike the four pointed [[Order of the Bath]] stars used by the army which are often referred to as "pips".}} as in the equivalent Royal Navy insignia. Prior to 1995, the RAN shoulder board was identical to the [[Vice Admiral#United Kingdom|UK]] shoulder board. (The UK shoulder board changed in 2001.)
